 develop personal bonds with their brothers and sisters that stay strong well past graduation &ndash; often for a lifetime. </font></p><font size=\"1\">  </font><p><font size=\"1\">Your gift will help strengthen these bonds, making the Greek experience even more memorable.</font></p><font size=\"1\">  </font><p><font size=\"1\">You can designate your gift to an individual Greek organization or to the Greek Life General Fund, which supports all Greek organizations on campus. In addition, you can choose how your gift will be used.&nbsp;<em> </em></font></p><font size=\"1\">      </font><p><font size=\"1\"><em><u><a href=\"https://www.rit.edu/development/giving/greekgiving.php\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Click here to donate!\">Click here to donate!</a></u></em> </font></p></td></tr></tbody></table><strong>Message From the Office of Fraternity &amp; Sorority Life</strong><br /><br />Rochester Institute of Technology is home to 30 diverse inter/national and local organizations. These Greek organizations offer students an opportunity to enhance college life in a unique environment. Commitment to personal and organizational excellence is the cornerstone for a RIT Greek experience. Greek membership is a valuable opportunity for personal, intellectual and social development.<br /><br />Each fraternity and sorority shares a deep commitment toward development of the individual members as well as the entire chapter. Throughout the past year, RIT Greek have promoted scholarship, actively participated in a variety of community service projects, raised money for their national philanthropies, competed in athletic and intramural sports and socialized with other organizations.<br /><br /><br /> <br /><br /> <img src=\"/main/admin/editPage/images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" />','2010-09-28 09:57:12','greek','fratsorlife','index','Fraternity & Sorority Life'),(25,0,'<p>The support our clubs and organizations receive from the faculty and staff members across RIT who agree to serve as advisors is invaluable.  Making connections, sharing information and history, and providing accurate and important referral to additional organization resources are all critical and core to the success of an advisor and their organization! We are grateful to the many faculty, staff, and administrators who service our campus and programs as advisors, and seek to provide you support and guidance in your efforts.  Please review the information on our website, and do not hesitate to contact us with any questions or clarifications you might need.  To better direct your questions and expedite gathering the information you need, contact:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<table cellspacing=\"12\">\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><b>Jessica Berner</b> for Fraternity and Sorority<br />advising questions.</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-size:12px;\">Phone: 5-7123 <br />Email: jrbccl@rit.edu</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><b>Ryan Giglia</b> for Club advising questions.</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-size:12px;\">Phone: 5-7685 <br />Email:  rjgccl@rit.edu</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-size:12px;\"><b>Karey Pine</b> for Major Student Organization<br />(MSO) advising questions.</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"font-size:12px;\">Phone: 5-6230 <br />Email: ktprla@rit.edu</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n<strong>Manuals<br />  </strong><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/clubs/resources/ClubAdvisorHandbook.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Advisor Handbook\">Advisor Handbook<br /></a><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/advisors/advising_guidelines.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Advising Guidelines\">Advising Guideline for Student Organizations within the Division of Student Affairs</a><br /> <br /> <br /> <strong>Formation and Recognition Forms<br /></strong><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/clubs/resources/Application%20for%20Recognition%202007-08.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"App: Club Recognition\">Application for RIT Club Recognition</a><br /><br /> <br /> <strong>Budget<br /> <br /></strong><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/clubs/resources/Club%20Budget%202007-08.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Budget Process\">Budget Process</a><br /><img src=\"images/powerpoint.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"ms powerpoint\" /> <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/clubs/resources/Club%20Budget%202007_2008.ppt\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Budget Presentation\">Budget Presentation</a><br /> <br /> <br /> <strong>Add to Your Calendar<br /></strong><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"docs/ImportantDates%202007-08.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Important Dates\">Important Dates<br /></a>   <br /><br /><br />  <em><a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/acrobat/readstep2.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"images/getacro2.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Get Adobe Acrobat\" align=\"left\" /></a><br /><br /><br /></em>Note: You may need to <strong><a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/acrobat/readstep2.html\" target=\"_blank\">download Acrobat Reader</a></strong> before viewing a document in PDF format.<br /> <br /> ','2007-08-03 15:04:52','1','advisor','index','Advisor Information'),(26,0,'staff goes here','2010-09-13 11:18:28','mas1042','about','profstaff','Professional Staff'),(27,0,'<p>student staff goes here</p>','2007-06-04 15:38:33','1','about','studentstaff','Student Staff'),(28,0,'<a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/advisors/advising_guidelines.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><br /> </a>','2007-07-20 09:51:32','1','advisor','forms','Forms'),(29,0,'<p>AFA</p><p>FIPG </p>','2007-07-27 17:25:36','1','advisor','links','Links'),(31,0,'<strong>Mission</strong> <p>Build a framework for personal growth by encouraging a commitment to social development, personal responsibility and respect for others. Foster a strong sense of community within the Greek system and the extended RIT university. Nurture a learning community where scholarship, leadership and self-discovery thrive. Provide a self governance structure that both anticipates and responds to changing contemporary needs. Strive to make the Greek system a source of pride for the RIT community. Demonstrate a strong service ethic through ongoing support of the local community. Promote an inclusive community of diverse student cultures. </p><p><strong>Vision</strong>  </p><p>We, the Greek Community of RIT, exist to foster the intellectual, social, and ethical development of our members in an environment that promotes a lifelong relationship and commitment to fraternity and university.   </p><p><strong>Values</strong>      </p><p>* Learning and Scholarship<br />* Leadership and Personal Growth     <br />* Diversity and Appreciation of Differences     <br />* Charity and Service to Others     <br />* Lifelong Friendships and Communal Traditions   </p><p><strong>Fun Facts About Greek Life</strong>  </p><p>* 85 percent of the Fortune 500 executives are members of Greek organizations.</p><p>* 25 United States Presidents have belonged to Greek-letter organizations.</p><p>* Fraternities and sororities have maintained a higher grade point average than the undergraduate average at most universities.  </p><p>* Greek organization members have a higher graduation rate than non-members.  </p><p>* A study by the Center for the Study of College Fraternities found that fraternity and sorority members we significantly more satisfied with their college experience than non-members.  </p><p>* 63 percent of the U.S. President&#39;s cabinet since 1900 has been fraternity men. </p><p>* 77 percent of Who&#39;s Who in America is Greek.</p>','2007-10-24 09:40:44','1','fratsorlife','gogreek','Go Greek!'),(64,0,'<p>The Governing Councils at Rochester Institute of Technology are comprised from College Panhellenic Council, Interfraternity Council, GAMMA, National Pan-Hellenic Counci, National Association of Latino Fraternal Organizations and Greek Council. These are the governing bodies of all Greek organizations at RIT. The Governing Councils are responsible for planning many fun and exciting All-Greek programs throughout the year.<strong><br /> <br /><br />  Find out more information on Governing Councils</strong> <br /><br /> <img src=\"/main/admin/editPage/images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />  <a href=\"http://www.ritpanhellenic.com/\">College Panhellenic Council</a><br /> <br />      		<img src=\"/main/admin/editPage/images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />  <a href=\"https://ritifc.celect.org/home\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Interfraternity Council\">Interfraternity Council</a><br /> <br />      		<img src=\"/main/admin/editPage/images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />  <a href=\"http://ritgreek.com/home\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"GAMMA - Greeks Advocating the Mature Management of Alcohol\">GAMMA</a><br /> <br />      		  <img src=\"/main/admin/editPage/images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />  <a href=\"http://ritnphc.com/welcome\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"National Pan-Hellenic Council\">National Pan-Hellenic Council<br /></a><br />   <img src=\"/main/admin/editPage/images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" /><a href=\"http://ritnalfo.com/home\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"National Association of Latino Fraternal Organizations\">National Association of Latino Fraternal Organizations</a><br /><br />  <img src=\"/main/admin/editPage/images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />  <a href=\"http://ritgreek.com/home\">Greek Council</a><br />   <br /> <br /> <br /> </p><p><br /> <br /> <br /> </p>','2010-09-15 09:56:08','greek','fratsorlife','councils','Governing Councils'),(32,0,'<p><strong>Find out more about Fraternity and Sorority Life!<br /> </strong><a href=\"fratsorlife/forms\"><strong><br /> </strong></a><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />        <a href=\"fratsorlife/benefits\" title=\"Benefits of Greek Life\">Benefits of Greek Life<br /></a><br /><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />    <a href=\"fratsorlife/forms\" title=\"Important Resources\">Forms, Constitutions, Policies, Links</a><br /> <br /><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />    <a href=\"fratsorlife/parents\" title=\"Information for Parents\">For Parents</a><br /> <br /><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />      <a href=\"fratsorlife/terms\" title=\"Greek Alphabet and Terms\">Greek Alphabet and Terms</a><br /><a href=\"fratsorlife/parents\"></a><br /><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />     <a href=\"fratsorlife/recruitment\" title=\"Membership Recruitment Process\">Membership Recruitment Process</a><br /> <br /><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />    <a href=\"fratsorlife/programs\" title=\"Programs\">Programs</a><br /> <br /> <img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />    <a href=\"fratsorlife/tips\">Recruitment Tips</a></p><p><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />   <a href=\"fratsorlife/between\">Between The Columns </a></p><a href=\"fratsorlife/tips\"></a><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><br /><br /> </strong><br /> <br /> </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>','2008-09-16 12:37:18','1','fratsorlife','resources','Resources'),(33,0,'<strong>Welcome members of the RIT Greek Community! </strong><br /> <br /> We have developed this application especially for presidents and members of RIT Greek Organizations. Here you can modify, update, and view important information about your organization. In addition, you can now submit your quarterly reports online. <br /> <p><br /> Please use the link below to sign in and navigate to the site.<br /> <br /> <img src=\"images/sign_icon.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"sign in\" title=\"sign in\" align=\"left\" />    <a href=\"https://webapps.rit.edu/cas/login?service=http://campuslife.rit.edu/getconnected/\" title=\"Greek Connection\">Sign in to Greek Connection</a><br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> </p>','2007-09-01 12:31:47','1','fratsorlife','connection','Greek Connection'),(34,0,'The Center for Campus Life cosponsors special events and performances for RIT and the Rochester Community. Our goal is to promote diversity, world cultures, and events that all people can come and enjoy. We provide campus events ranging from concerts to diversity weeks to speakers. There are multiple events each month to take part in and celebrate. <br /><br /><strong>What events are coming up?!</strong><br /><strong><a href=\"specialevents/pas\"><br /></a></strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp; <a href=\"specialevents/pas\">Performing Artist Series<br /></a><strong><a href=\"specialevents/css\"><br /></a></strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"specialevents/css\">Cultural Spotlight Series</a><br /> <br /> <strong>Ticket Information</strong><br /> <br /> Tickets can be purchased: <ul>   <li><span><em>At the Bytes on the Run[Call- 475-5210] ( Former Book store in Student Alumni Union ) </em>or at the door on performance night, if available. For VISA/MC , call the field house box office at (585) 475-4121.</span></li> </ul> <ul>   <li> Through the <strong><a href=\"http://www.rit.edu/~field/specialEvents_tickets.php3\" title=\"Tickets: Gordon Field House Box Office\">Gordon Field House Box Office</a></strong> in person, or by phone at 585.475.4121.</li> </ul> <ul>   <li> Through <a href=\"http://www.ticketmaster.com/venue/64\" title=\"Ticketmaster\"><strong>Ticketmaster</strong></a> (outlet, online, or charge by phone 585.232.1900).<br /> (RIT discounted tickets are not available through Ticketmaster. An RIT ID<em> is required when purchasing RIT affiliated tickets at the Box Office.)</em></li> </ul> <p><strong><br /> How do I get to RIT?</strong></p><p><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"docs/campusmap.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Map of RIT Campus\">Map of RIT Campus</a><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"docs/saumap.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Map to Student Alumni Union\">Map to Student Alumni Union</a><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" /> <a href=\"docs/fullsau.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"SAU Building Layout\">Student Alumni Union Building Layout</a></p><p>Once entering campus at the main entrance off of Jefferson Road, follow the signs to the Visitor&#39;s Information Center. A Campus Safety officer will issue you a parking pass and provide directions to either D or U lot. </p>','2010-09-02 10:54:38','1','specialevents','index','Special Events'),(35,0,'<p class=\"p4\"><strong>Opening the 15th Season </strong><strong>(2009-2010)</strong><strong> at RIT!&nbsp; </strong></p>Beginning with two concerts in 1995-96, we have now expanded to an average of five concerts a year,  now called The Performing Artists Concert Series. David Perlman, an Electrical Engineering professor (now emeritus) runs the concert series along with the Center for Campus Life and has been able to draw top performers from the Rochester Philharmonic Orchestra, the Eastman School of Music, and a combination of other local and sometimes imported talent. It&#39;s purpose has been, from the beginning, to bring highly professional classical and jazz performers to the campus and to make playing opportunities available to talented artists who are somewhat unknown. Since an important goal is to make our music affordable, we&#39;ve been holding ticket prices down.<br /><p><br /><span><em>  Ticket Information:Tickets may be purchased at the Bytes on the Run[Call- 475-5210] ( Former Book store in Student Alumni Union ) </em>or at the door on performance night, if available. For VISA/MC , call the field house box office at (585) 475-4121.</span></p><p><span> <br />Students: $5.00<br />Faculty/ Staff/ Alumni : $15.00<br />Public: $20.00<br /><br /><br /><img src=\"images/SpecialEvents/RIT_PA_Logo.gif\" alt=\"Performing Artist Series Logo\" title=\"Performing Artist Series Logo\" align=\"top\" /><br /> <br /></span></p> <p class=\"p4\"><strong>Friday,Decmber 11th , 2009 at 8 pm</strong></p>  <p class=\"p6\"><strong>Jazz Impersonation of the Beatles<br /></strong></p>Pianist/arranger Rod Blumenau has created a jazz tribute to The Beatles that will premiere in the third concert of RIT&#39;s Performing Artists Concert Series on December 11th. He will be ably supported by Jeff Campbell (bass), Gabe Condon (guitar), and Brad Paxton (drums). The group will demonstrate how amazingly well 17 of the compositions of four musical illiterates (none of the Beatles could read music) sound in the jazz genre, four decades after the Beatles broke up. Selections include some of Lennon/McCartney&rsquo;s early material (&ldquo;She&rsquo;s a Woman&rdquo;, &ldquo;Things We Said Today&rdquo;, &ldquo;When I&rsquo;m 64&rdquo;), later works (&ldquo;Blackbird&rdquo;, &ldquo;Eleanor Rigby&rdquo;), and the song recorded by the most artists ever (according to the Guinness Book of World Records), &ldquo;Yesterday&rdquo;. Rod will also share interesting anecdotes about the process the Beatles used to create their timeless music.<p class=\"p4\">&nbsp;</p>  <p class=\"p4\"><strong>Ticket Prices</strong></p> <p class=\"p4\">Students $5<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p> <p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>Faculty/staff/alumni $15<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p> <p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>General Public $20</p> <p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>Tickets<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>will be available after September 7, 2009,<span><em> at the Bytes on the Run[Call- 475-5210] ( Former Book store in Student Alumni Union ) </em>or at the door on performance night</span> For VISA or Master Card phone orders (after September 7), call the RIT Field House Box Office at (585) 475-4121.</p>  <!--.. Season ..-->   <p class=\"p3\">&nbsp; </p><p class=\"p3\"><u><strong>Fifteenth Anniversary Season-- Mark your calendar. </strong></u></p> <p class=\"p2\">&nbsp;</p> <p class=\"p3\">1. September 25, 2009</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><strong>Louis &amp; Ella</strong></p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>Herb Smith (trumpet and vocal) Artistic Director</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span> <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; Joilet Harris (vocal)</span></p><p class=\"p3\">Rod Blumenau Quartet</p><p class=\"p3\">&nbsp; Rod Blumenau (piano)</p><p class=\"p3\">&nbsp; Jeff Campbell (bass)</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span> <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Brad Paxton (drums)</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">&nbsp; </span><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">Quinn Lawrence (sax)</span></p><p class=\"p3\">Michael Lasser, narration</p> <p class=\"p4\">&nbsp;</p> <p class=\"p3\">2. October 30, 2009</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><strong>Andrey Pisarev Returns- piano recital</strong></p> <div><font size=\"3\" class=\"Apple-style-span\"><span style=\"font-size: 12px\" class=\"Apple-style-span\">RIT&#39;s Performing Artists Concert Series is proud to  welcome back internationally acclaimed concert pianist Andrey Pisarev in  recital.&nbsp; Mr. Pisarev, a professor at the Moscow Conservatory of Music, has won  top prizes at the Mozart, Pretoria, and Busoni International Competitions, and  makes concert appearances world wide.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Pisarev will be performing the 12  separate pieces comprising The Seasons, Op. 37 by Tchaikovsky.&nbsp; The second half  of his concert will be devoted to Chopin with performances of Two Nocturnes, Op.  55 and the Sonata in B minor, Op. 58.</span></font> </div><p class=\"p5\">&nbsp;</p><p class=\"p5\">Note: On November 1,<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Mr. Pisarev will be performing the Schumann Piano Quintet with Chamber Music Rochester at the Hochstein Performance Hall.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Reduced price tickets will be available at the RIT recital.</p> <p class=\"p4\">&nbsp;</p> <p class=\"p3\">3. December 11, 2009</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><strong>Jazz Impressions of the Beatles</strong></p>Pianist/arranger Rod Blumenau has created a jazz tribute to The Beatles that will premiere in the third concert of RIT&#39;s Performing Artists Concert Series on December 11th. He will be ably supported by Jeff Campbell (bass), Gabe Condon (guitar), and Brad Paxton (drums). The group will demonstrate how amazingly well 17 of the compositions of four musical illiterates (none of the Beatles could read music) sound in the jazz genre, four decades after the Beatles broke up. Selections include some of Lennon/McCartney&rsquo;s early material (&ldquo;She&rsquo;s a Woman&rdquo;, &ldquo;Things We Said Today&rdquo;, &ldquo;When I&rsquo;m 64&rdquo;), later works (&ldquo;Blackbird&rdquo;, &ldquo;Eleanor Rigby&rdquo;), and the song recorded by the most artists ever (according to the Guinness Book of World Records), &ldquo;Yesterday&rdquo;. Rod will also share interesting anecdotes about the process the Beatles used to create their timeless music.<p class=\"p3\">4. April 2, 2010</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><strong>Four Classic Stars</strong></p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>Soojin Ahn (piano)</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>Michael Larco (viola)</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>Rachel Barton Pine (violin)</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>Wendy Warner (cello)</p> <p class=\"p4\">&nbsp;</p> <p class=\"p3\">5. April 30, 2010</p> <p class=\"p3\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span> <strong>The Ying Quartet</strong></p><p><br /><strong><br />Additional Information</strong><a href=\"http://www.davidigital.com/concert\" target=\"_blank\"></a><br /><br />Contact:<span>  </span>David Perlman</p><p> 585.381.3543</p><p> e-mail: <a href=\"mailto:dnpeee@sprintmail.com\">dnpeee@sprintmail.com</a></p><strong><strong><br /></strong></strong>','2009-11-11 12:49:51','1','specialevents','pas','Performing Artist Series'),(36,0,'<p><u><strong>Hispanic Hertitage Month 2009</strong></u></p><p>September 15th to October 15th 2009 </p><p>A month of mostly Free Events , celebrating the hispanic culture. </p><p>Events sponsored by the RIT Center for Campus Life , North Star Center, and Department of Foriegn Languages with co-sponsors including the Women&#39;s Center Center, Hispanic Deaf Club, AALANA Collegiate<br />Association, the Latin American Student Association, Los Hermanos de Latino American Unida/Lambda<br />Alpha Upsilon Fraternity, Inc., Las Hermanas de Latinas Promoviendo Comunidad/Lambda Pi Chi Sorority,<br />Inc., the NTID Student Life team, and the RIT Chief Diversity Office.</p>  <p>&nbsp;<a href=\"../../images/SpecialEvents/Hispanic_Heritage_Calendar.gif\">Click here to view the Calendar of Events </a> </p>  Interpreting services provided upon request. Please visit MyAccess.rit.edu 1-2 weeks in advance to request services.<br /><p><em>For more information contact Stephanie Paredes at sxpnsc@rit.edu Carol Reed at cjr2033@rit.edu.</em> </p>','2009-08-25 12:09:12','1','specialevents','css','Cultural Spotlight Series'),(73,0,'<strong>Request Creative Services</strong><br /><br />The Center for Campus Life has a staff of highly creative student artists. Our creative team offers various services for clubs, organizations, Student Affairs, and major student events FREE of charge. Artists are responsible for design only. Printing and copying are the responsibility of the requestor.<p><em>Our services include:</em></p><p>Flyers<br />Posters<br />Banners<br />Signs<br />Logos<br />Table Tents<br />Tickets<br />Reporter Ads<br />LCD Screen Slides</p><p><br /><br /><br /><strong>Artist Request Forms</strong><br /><br />To submit an online request, visit <a href=\"/art_request\" target=\"_blank\">http://campuslife.rit.edu/art_request</a>. Due to the number of requests we receive, please turn in your request <em>at least</em> one week before your event.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','2010-09-03 16:55:17','cclwww','about','artistrequests','Artist Requests'),(37,0,'<p class=\"MsoNormal\">RIT Tech Crew is an event technical production department whose staff is comprised entirely of student employees managed by two RIT staff members. Tech Crew&#39;s parent department is the Center for Campus Life; its primary mission is to support on-campus student activities. Our services also extend to support the production needs of the entire RIT community providing lighting, sound, staging, and power distribution for special events ranging from dance parties, to lectures, to rock concerts, to commencement.</p><br />\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Tech Crew employs about 60 students during the school year and owns various production equipment. Additionally, Tech Crew works closely with various outside production companies subcontracted to work on campus.</p><br />\r\n\r\n<p>If you are looking for information about contracting Tech Crew&rsquo;s services, or about registering an event on campus, please contact Event Registration behind the Info Desk in building 4. Our Business Office is located in the basement of the Student Alumni Union (Building 4) across from the Music Room. The room number is 04-A220 and our Business Office phone number is 585.475.2257. Our email address is <a href=\"mailto:techcrew@rit.edu\">techcrew@rit.edu</a> and our Business Office hours vary from quarter to quarter depending on student coordinator schedule. </p><br />','2007-08-16 15:26:39','1','techcrew','index','Tech Crew'),(38,0,'<p>Tech Crew provides a variety of services to support events held on the RIT campus. We operate out of the Student-Alumni Union (located in the A-Level backstage of Ingle Auditorium) and support on average 600+ events annually. The events can be anything from a small meeting or luncheon to a large-scale concert. We provide or can arrange for, including set up and operation:\r\n</p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Staging</strong>      &ndash; We have over 2,500 square feet of stage risers ranging from 16&rdquo; to 24&rdquo;      high, and can arrange through vendors for stage risers 16&rdquo; to 72&rdquo; in height. <br />\r\n</p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Sound      Systems</strong> &ndash; Our sound systems range from simple speakers on aluminum      support stands for simple events such as a podium/microphone for a lecture      in a medium size room to an array of concert grade high powered 4-way      system used for concerts or public address for 7,000 persons in the Field      House. Our inventory of mixing consoles (from a 4-channel mike mixers to a      state-of-the-art digital 48-channel desk), microphones, stands, signal      processing equipment and stage monitors can provide for several events      operating on campus simultaneously or can be used to support just about      any type of gig. <br />\r\n</p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stage      Lighting</strong> &ndash; Equipment includes several small (6 to 12) channel dimmers      to a 48 channel unit as well as several control consoles that can operate      anywhere from 24 to several hundred dimmer channels. Lighting fixtures      include Fresnel, Ellipsoidal, PAR56 and PAR64; over 400 fixtures to meet      concert or theatrical requirements. <br />\r\n</p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Rigging      Equipment/Services</strong> &ndash; The sound and lighting systems used in all      smaller venues are ground supported using industry standard utility lifts.      In the large venues (Gym and Ice Arena), some lighting may be flown (hung)      from the ceiling, and in the Field House, these systems as well as sound      loudspeaker arrays are typically flown rather than ground supported due to      the larger audience capacity. Equipment includes industry standard ground      support lifts, chain motors, lighting trussing (both triangular and box),      cabling, hardware, etc. We also have scaffold sections that can be used      for constructing sets, rigging projection screens; or placing      loudspeakers, projectors, etc. where they need to be elevated. Please note      that all rigging hang points in the Gordon Field House are done by local      union certified riggers. \r\n</p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Electrical      Power Distribution</strong> &ndash; In several venues we have electrical services      installed where we connect portable electrical distribution panels to      provide multiple circuits for expositions, LAN parties, support for      catering or other departments working the event that is in need of      electrical power.\r\n</p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Dance      Floor</strong> &ndash; The portable dance floor is comprised of 3&rsquo;x3&rsquo; oak parquet      interlocking sections and can provide up to 900 square feet of dance area.      It is only available in the SAU or Clark Gym. </p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Theatrical      Support</strong> &ndash; In Ingle Auditorium we have the use of all the equipment      mentioned above, plus a carpenter shop, soft goods, additional lighting,      intercom systems, etc. necessary for a theatrical production. </p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Backline      Equipment </strong>&ndash; Through outside vendors, we can arrange for backline      equipment (drum sets, keyboards, pianos, guitar amplifiers or other large      instruments that generally are not carried on flights) for performers. </p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stagehands</strong>      &ndash; Our crew of 50 experienced employees can provide necessary support for      events even if an outside production company is used. <br />Note: We also manage and operate Ingle Auditorium. Services in Ingle include all of the above plus video projection. </p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Facilities we typically operate in:</strong></p>  <ul style=\"margin-top: 0in\"><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Student-Alumni      Union (all areas)</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Gordon      Field House</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Clark Gymnasium</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Ritter      Ice Arena</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Interfaith      Center</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Watson      Dining Hall</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">CIMS</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Outside      Programming Areas<br /> </li></ul>    \r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Type of events supported:</strong></p>  \r\n<ul style=\"margin-top: 0in\"><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Banquets</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Conferences</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Lectures</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Presentations</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Expositions</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Concerts</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Social      Functions</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Theatre</li></ul>  \r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Note: We do not rent or loan equipment out for set up or operation by others. We do not provide video projection or production as that is provided by ETC (Educational  Technology Center), x5-2551, located in the basement of the Wallace Library; but do work with and support them in providing any necessary rigging, electrical or audio interface that may be needed. Typically, we do not support instructional (class room) needs as they are also provided by ETC. </p> <br />\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Estimates</strong><br /><br />Our costs are based on hours worked. Many typical smaller jobs have a &lsquo;set&rsquo; cost that is based on average labor worked for that type of set up. Most all of the larger events (ones that will take over 40 or 50 employee hours will be estimated, but charged on the actual hours assigned to the job. In order for us to be able to provide an accurate estimate, there is a lot of information (there is never too much information that you can provide) we will need, including: </p> <br />\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-top: 0in\"><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Event      name and a good description of what it is about if not obvious</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Contact      info</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Date</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Facility</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Times      of event</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Times      of room reservations (to allow for our set up and tear down)</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Type      of event (lecture, movie, concert, etc.)</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Name      of artist, speaker, etc., and a copy of the contract with technical rider      and/or artist&rsquo;s agent name and phone number</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">A      schedule or a &ldquo;marching order&rdquo; of events to take place on stage</li><li class=\"MsoNormal\">Equipment      needs in addition to any contract rider<br /><br /></li></ul>    \r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Making Reservations</strong><br /><br />Although we can generally provide services for multiple events at the same time, it does depend on what staffing is available (remember, our crew has classes too), equipment that is reserved for another event, and adequate time for us to plan the job and assign a crew; we recommend contacting us as early as possible, minimally we recommend two weeks but can be several months. We do operate on a first come &ndash; first served basis.<br /><br />We are located in the A-Level of the Student-Alumni Union, Room A220 (follow the signs once inside the area). Our business hours generally are Monday through Friday 9:00 am to 4:00 pm, except during breaks and holidays. We can be reached via email at <a href=\"mailto: techcrew@rit.edu\"> techcrew@rit.edu</a> or telephone 585.475.2257.</p>  <br /> \r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">All student organization events supported by Tech Crew must adhere to the Event Registration guidelines/policies. </p> <br />','2007-08-08 15:29:41','1','techcrew','services','Services'),(39,0,'Here you can find typical room setups of campus events varying in size from a dance party in the Student Alumni Union Cafeteria to a large concert in Gordon Field House.  These examples of room setups can help you determine what space would be most appropriate for your event.<br /><br /><strong><br />Setup in SAU Cafeteria<br /></strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;        <a href=\"techcrew/cafe\" title=\"Setup in SAU Cafe\">More information</a><strong><br /></strong><br /><img src=\"images/TechCrew/smallevent.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"SAU Cafe\" title=\"SAU Cafe\" /><br /><br /><br /><strong>Typical concert setup in Clark Gym<br /></strong><em>Click on the image to take a closer look!</em><br /><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;        <a href=\"techcrew/clarkgym\" title=\"Setup in Clark Gym\">More Information</a><em><br /></em><br /><a href=\"Movies/TechCrewClarkConcertVR.mov\"><img src=\"images/TechCrew/mediumevent.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Clark Gym\" title=\"Clark Gym\" /></a><br /><br /><p><strong>Setup in Gordon Field House<br /></strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;        <a href=\"techcrew/fieldhouse\" title=\"Setup in Gordon Field House\">More Information</a><strong><br /></strong><br /><img src=\"images/TechCrew/largeevent.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Gordon Field House\" title=\"Gordon Field House\" /><br /><br /><strong><br />Typical Room Setup in Fireside Lounge</strong><br /><img src=\"images/link.gif\" alt=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;      <a href=\"techcrew/fireside\">More Information<br /><br /></a></p><strong><br />Typical Room Setup in Ingle Auditorium<br /></strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" alt=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;      <a href=\"techcrew/ingleauditorium\" title=\"Room Setups in Ingle Auditorium\">More Information</a><br /><br /><img src=\"images/TechCrew/ingleaud.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Ingle Auditorium \" title=\"Ingle Auditorium \" /><br /><strong><br /><br />Typical Room Setup in Ritz Sports Zone <br /></strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" alt=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;      <a href=\"techcrew/ritz\" title=\"Room Setups in Ritz\">More Information</a><br /><br /><img src=\"images/TechCrew/ritz.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Ritz Sports Zone\" />','2007-08-16 15:42:27','1','techcrew','setups','Room Setups'),(40,0,'<p>Tech Crew employs about 60 students during the school year in the positions of supervisors, technicians and production assistants. In addition, there is the possibility of alumni/freelance positions.</p><br />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nIf you are interested in a position with Tech Crew please contact Rich Morse or Rick Wyffels  via email at <a href=\"mailto:techcrew.edu\">techcrew.edu</a> or telephone 585.475.2257.\r\n</p><br />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n<img src=\"images/TechCrew/techcrew.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Tech Crew\" /><br />\r\n<em>Members from last year&#39;s tech crew with Carlos Mencia</em> \r\n\r\n</p>','2007-08-06 11:04:33','1','techcrew','employment','Employment'),(41,0,'<p><strong>Question #1: When, where and how much does it cost to vend at RIT?</strong><br /> 	Vending occurs at RIT Monday through Friday in Grace Watson Hall and on Thursdays and Fridays in the Student Alumni Union.</p>       <p>Vendors who choose to vend at Grace Watson Hall must bring their own tables and are paying for the space they are using. The cost of one table space is $50, a second and third table space(s) are $6 each. A vendor can have a maximum of three spaces per vending day. The vending hours for Grace Watson Hall are 9:00 AM - 7:00 PM.</p>       <p>Vendors who choose to vend at the Student Alumni Union will find six-foot tables set up for them when they arrive to vend at RIT. One table is $50, while second and third tables are $6 each. A vendor can have a maximum of three tables per vending day. The vending hours for the Student Alumni Union are 9:00 AM- 4:30 PM.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>            <p><strong>Question #2: What are the benefits of vending at RIT?</strong><br />     Vending at RIT gives vendors access to over 15,000 students, faculty and staff.</p>       <p>A student group may be assigned to each vendor to enhance the vendor&#39;s experience and help promote for the vendors products or services.</p>       <p>Each of the vending location is conveniently located near a popular campus cafeteria.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>            <p><strong>Question #3: What happens if a vendor makes a reservation and needs to cancel it?</strong><br /> A vendor can cancel any reservation they make; however, they must confirm this cancellation with the Vending Office a minimum of 24 hours before the reservation. If a vendor does not follow the 24 hour prior cancellation rule they may not be allowed to vend at RIT in the future and/or they may be charged a cancellation fee.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>       	 <p><strong>Question #4: Where do vendors unload their products and park while vending at RIT?</strong><br /> Vendors MUST unload behind the Student Alumni Union near Lot U. Vendors should stop at the Visitors Information Center, located on the North side of campus near the front of the SAU, to pick up a parking pass for Lot U for the day(s) they are vending.</p>       <p>Vendors may unload in front of Grace Watson Hall and park in the spaces available near Grace Watson Hall. Vendors should pick up a parking pass at the Public Safety Office in Grace Watson Hall.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>            <p><strong>Question #5: What can be expected of the student organizations from the vendors?</strong><br /> Vendors are allowed to ask their assigned student organization to help promote for them through hanging flyers and posters around campus. Vendors are also allowed to ask a student organization to help them unload and set up, clean up and load their vehicles, and to give them a break during the middle of the day. Your organization must be prepared to meet all of these requirements when you agree to be a vending sponsor.<br /> <br /> <br /> <img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp; <a href=\"sau/vending\">Back to RIT Vending</a> </p>','2007-08-10 12:32:40','1','sau','faq','Services | RIT Vending | FAQ'),(51,0,'<strong>You Probably Have Some Questions...<br /> </strong><br /> Perceptions of fraternities and sororities tend to differ widely among both parents and students. Hopefully these responses will begin to clarify some of those perceptions and, at the same time, provide you with the answers to some of the questions most commonly asked by parents.<br /> <br />  <p><strong>Won&rsquo;t a fraternity or sorority have an adverse effect on my student&rsquo;s grades?<br />   </strong><br /> Actually, it&rsquo;s more likely that a fraternity or sorority will help your student&rsquo;s grades. When a student joins a fraternity or sorority, he or she becomes a part of a larger group of students who have already made it through their first year at RIT. Not only does the group understand what a first-year student is facing, but they can also provide assistance in most of the courses your student will be taking. There are few other places where a student can gain access to the variety of resources that the Greek community can provide. Ultimately, the responsibility for succeeding in the classroom is the individual student&rsquo;s. With the broad range of resources available within the Greek community, however, students are more likely to achieve their academic potential.<br /> <br />  </p> 		   		<p><strong>Are Greeks really like the actors in ANIMAL HOUSE? <br /> </strong><br /> Many people have the misconception that the image of Greek organizations depicted in Animal House is really what is happening on college campuses across America. In reality, the Animal House image of Greek Life could not be further from the truth. The RIT Greek community focuses on responsibility in our activities. The university promotes alcohol responsibility in a number of ways; including sponsoring a national educational organization called Greeks Advocating the Mature Management of Alcohol (GAMMA) as well as many national risk management speakers. Although an individual&rsquo;s actions are entirely up to him/her, Greeks hold their members accountable for their actions and use their founding principals as guides in their activities.<br /> <br />  </p> 		   		<p><strong>What does being Greek really mean?<br />  </strong><br /> Membership in a Greek letter organization is a lifetime obligation. Choosing the Greek community means working with a group of men or women who can exchange and stand for common goals and ideas while being held to a higher standard than other college students. The Greek experience during the college years is a gateway to many rewards and connections later in life. Each chapter develops a special bond called brotherhood and sisterhood. Both are nurtured thorough common work, laughter, service projects, intramurals and the shared success and frustrations of all. Throughout the student&rsquo;s life, membership will be an unwritten bond of friendship no matter what course his/her life takes.<br /> <br />  </p> 		   		<p><strong>Does it cost a lot to be Greek?<br />  </strong><br /> Joining a fraternity or sorority does carry a financial commitment. Each chapter is self-supporting through dues paid by their members. When students join a Greek letter organization, they also agree to pay dues and fees while in school to maintain membership. Although chapters may make accommodations for special needs, students should discuss the financial obligations with their parent(s) before deciding to join. Each chapter has different dues for membership that cover such things as chapter and national dues, due to the Interfraternity, Panhellenic, and National Pan-Hellenic Councils, social activities, resources and other miscellaneous costs.<br /> <br />  </p> 		   		<p><strong>What about hazing and alcohol abuse?<br /> </strong> <br /> Hazing is a big concern to parents. RIT and New York State Law prohibit hazing of any kind. New members experience a period of orientation. During this time, your child will attend a new member retreat to learn about hazing, leadership retreats, community service projects, and activities designed to build friendships among the new members and the older members. Each new member is asked to sign an anti-hazing statement stating that they will not allow themselves to be hazed and will report any such wrongdoing. Hazing will not be tolerated! </p> 		   		<p>Alcohol abuse is unhealthy and inconsistent with fraternity and sorority ideals. All fraternities and sororities are expected to uphold state, county, city laws, and university policies regarding the consumption of alcohol. In addition, chapters are not allowed to purchase alcohol for their members due to national risk-management policies. The Interfraternity, Panhellenic, and National Pan-Hellenic councils will also take proper actions against the chapter if alcohol is being abused.&nbsp;</p> 		   		<p><strong>Won&rsquo;t working while in school conflict with participation in a fraternity or sorority?</strong></p><p><br /> Actually, many students involved in the RIT Greek community are also employed outside of the classroom. In today&rsquo;s world, the reality is that only the lucky few can afford to attend college without outside employment. Fraternities and sororities recognize that it is important for members to be able to meet their financial obligations and that many students will work to help finance their educations. Working students can still take advantage of the opportunities available through the Greek community.<br /> <br />  </p> 		   		<p><strong>Who is actually in charge of the fraternity or sorority?<br /> </strong><br /> Fraternity and sorority members elected to officer positions manage the day-to-day operations of the organization. These officers are assisted by members serving on committees and by alumni who act as advisors. In addition, most Greek organizations at RIT are part of a national organization which offers support, advice, and direction through a paid professional staff and regional volunteers. Professional staff from the university are employed to assist and monitor the activities of Greek organizations. As you can see a variety of individuals oversee the operations of the fraternity.<br /> <br />  </p> 		   		<p><strong>What is my role as a parent?<br /> </strong><br /> Be supportive and learn as much as you can by asking questions of your son or daughter as he/she meets people through the recruitment/intake process. Also be an active parent during your child&rsquo;s years in a fraternity or sorority. Remember, being in a fraternity or sorority can only benefit your child. Encourage and support your child. Greek members will be more than happy to tell him or her (and you) about their group. If you ever have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to contact the Greek Advisor.</p>','2007-07-09 15:02:23','1','fratsorlife','parents','Resources | For Parents'),(50,0,'<p><strong>The Club Resource Center serves a variety of purposes</strong><br /> <br />At the Club Resource Center you can: 		</p><ul><li>Pick up petty cash and checks</li><li>Hand in Expense Approval Forms (EAF)</li><li>Hand in Club Recognition and Intent to Form applications</li><li>Hand in Applications for Additional Funds (AFAF)</li><li>Make appointments with club financial staff</li><li>Get your questions answered</li><li>Make deposits</li><li>Drop off receipts and VISA cards</li><li>Hand in annual Club Budgets </li><li>Get a club statement printout and account balance</li><li>Find out if your club is frozen and why</li><li>Pick up blank club forms including EAFs, AFAFs, W-9 forms, tax exempt forms, mileage forms, etc.</li><li>Find out about important club dates</li><li>Get information about Finance Certification<br /><br /></li></ul> <table border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" width=\"349\" height=\"121\"> 	<tbody><tr> 		<td width=\"100\" valign=\"left\">Location:<br /><br /></td> 		<td>Campus Center 1st Floor<br /></td> 	</tr> 	<tr> 		<td valign=\"left\">Phone:<br /><br /></td> 		<td>585.475.4111<br /><br /></td> 	</tr> <tr> 		<td valign=\"left\">E.Mail:<br /><br /></td> 		<td><a href=\"mailto:infosg@rit.edu\">infosg@rit.edu<br /> </a><br /></td> 	</tr> <tr> 		 <td>Regular Hours:<br /><br /> </td> 		 <td><p>Monday- Thursday: 10 a.m. -7 p.m.<br />Friday: 10 a.m. - 4:30 p.m. </p></td>	 </tr>  </tbody> </table> <p>&nbsp;</p><p>Summer Hours:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Monday-Friday 10 a.m. - 4:30p.m.</p><br /><br /><br /><br />  ','2010-09-02 10:49:24','1','clubs','sginfo','Resources | Club Resource Center'),(62,0,'<strong>Leadership<br /> </strong><br /> The Greek community is dedicated to building future societal leaders by providing a wealth of leadership opportunities for Greek members. From social issues to academic, business to philanthropy, the leaders of today are gaining their leadership edge from their fraternity and sorority experiences. <p> Membership in a fraternal or sororal organization is one of the most outstanding means of discovering and refining your leadership potential. Within each chapter, members have the chance to assume a wide spectrum of leadership roles. These roles may range from serving as rush chair to treasurer, social chair to president. Within each fraternity exists anywhere from five to twenty different leadership positions, all requiring different degrees of skills and investments. Opportunities to learn and practice leadership stretch beyond chapters. </p>  		 <p> There are many system-wide leadership roles open on the Greek Council, IFC, NPC and the NPHC. Beyond the Greek community, fraternity men and sorority women are involved in many other organizations on campus. Some of these include Student Government, athletic teams, and many student clubs.<br /> <br />  </p>  		 		 <p> 		<strong>Philanthropy and Community Service<br /> </strong><br /> Philanthropy projects are events in which the Greek communities as a whole, or as individual chapters, donate their time and efforts to raise funds to benefit some worthwhile cause. </p>  		 <p> Chapters on campus plan many philanthropy and community service projects during the year to benefit a variety of agencies. One of the big philanthropy projects that the Greek community does every quarter is &quot;Adopt a Highway&quot; on East River Road. </p>  		 <p> Most chapters require members to maintain community service hours; yet these requirements are not a burden due to the satisfaction one gets when they have been completed. Philanthropy projects and community service are more than just helping out a cause. They show the community what Greeks are really like and they are a lot of fun for everybody involved.<br /> <br />  </p>  		 		 <p> 		<strong>Scholarship<br /> </strong><br /> Academic achievement is the first and foremost priority of all University students. Scholastic achievement is also central to the mission of most fraternities and sororities. Each fraternity or sorority places strong emphasis on creating an atmosphere conducive to high academic performance, as well as challenging each individual to live up to his and her highest academic potential. </p>  		 <p> Each fraternity and sorority generally implements various programs designed to assist members in their academic pursuits. Programs range from tutoring, help with scheduling, quiet study areas in the house, study tables for new members, test files, and awards for good grades. </p>  		 <p> Additionally, most organizations provide some financial scholarships supported by their national organizations and local alumni groups. These efforts reinforce the belief that academic achievement is an integral part of the fraternity and sorority experience.<br /> <br />  </p>  		 		 <p> 		<strong>Alumni Networking<br /> </strong><br /> Greek membership is for a lifetime. One of the greatest benefits that comes with being a member of the Greek community are the relationships you make with alumni, which provide many opportunities for career networking and mentoring, not only with your initial job search but also throughout your career. Homecoming, chapter anniversary dinners, conferences, conventions, and other events foster interaction with alumni. Alumni/graduate chapters located throughout the nation provide opportunities for continued involvement after graduation. Because their Greek experience was so meaningful, many alumni &ldquo;give back&rdquo; to their organization by volunteering their time on a chapter advisory board, housing corporations&rsquo; board, or as a regional or district officer.<br /> <br />  </p>  		 		 <p> 		<strong>Brotherhood/Sisterhood<br /> </strong><br /> Throughout your college experience at RIT, the friendships that our members make within their chapters are the ones that last a lifetime. Whether you came to college not knowing a single person or knowing several people, the opportunity to be a part of a brotherhood or sisterhood transcends your RIT college experience. </p>  		 <p> Brotherhood and sisterhood are the bonds of unity and friendship that last a lifetime. These bonds are not only among members for each individual chapter, but amongst chapters around the nation, due to the history and the ideals that each chapter was founded upon. </p>  		 <p> By becoming a member of the Greek community, you will meet people who will grow to become your closest friends; those who will cheer you on when you&rsquo;re successful and who will support you when the going gets tough. Lifelong friendships and associations are made through active participation in a Greek organization. </p>  		 <p> These relationships are deeper than going to parties, more meaningful than wearing the same letters. They are about growth and development of individuals as they begin their lives at RIT. Each new member brings his or her unique talents to the fraternity or sorority and is valued and respected for the way he or she is.<br /> <br />  </p>  		 		 <p> 		<strong>Social and Recreational Involvement<br /> </strong><br /> While academics are the main reason for one to attend RIT, you will achieve the best college experience possible through the proper balancing of academics and social activities. Joining a fraternity or sorority will offer you the most extensive social outlets possible on the RIT campus. Being Greek gives you the opportunity to meet new friends through participation in events like Brick City Festival, Alumni Weekends, Date Nights, Formals, Theme Parties, Greek Weekend and many other social activities. Fraternity men and sorority women pride themselves on the ability to help their fellow brothers and sisters develop socially and learn to have fun in a safe environment. </p>','2007-07-09 15:00:33','1','fratsorlife','benefits','Resources | Benefits of Greek Life'),(57,0,'<p><strong>How to form a Student Government Recognized Club</strong></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 12pt\" class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal\">If your group already has an advisor, please proceed to step 5.<span>  </span>If not, start at step 1.</span></strong></p>  <ol><li>Fill out an <strong><a href=\"/main/admin/editPage/clubs/resources\" title=\"App: Intent to Form\">Intent to Form Application</a></strong>, which can be found in the Center for Campus Life (CCL) office, located on the 2nd floor of the SAU RITreat, or on the <strong><a href=\"/main/admin/editPage/clubs/resources\" title=\"Just helping you out!\">Club Resources</a></strong> page.  Once this form has been approved, your organization then has the ability to reserve rooms in the SAU and advertise your meetings for three months.  You will be informed of Club Review Board&#39;s decision. </li><br /><li>Get as many people interested as you can with flyers and meetings.&nbsp; At this point you should be looking for an Advisor. This must be a full time RIT employee.<br /><br /></li><li>Once you have an Advisor, complete the <strong><a href=\"/main/admin/editPage/clubs/resources\" title=\"Do you want your club recognized?\">Application for RIT Club Recognition</a></strong> which can be found in the CCL office or on the <strong><a href=\"/main/admin/editPage/clubs/resources\" title=\"Just helping you out!\">Club Resources</a></strong> page.<br /><br /></li><li>At this point, you may want to draft a club constitution for effective leadership, and/or plan a basic operating budget.<br /><br /></li><li>Once the Application for Club Recognition is complete, turn it into the Campus Life Office or the SG Information Center (in the SAU RITreat). The Assistant Director for Campus Life Programs or the Clubs Graduate Assistant will then present the application to the <strong><a href=\"/main/admin/editPage/clubs/reviewboard\" title=\"Club Review Board\">Club Review Board (CRB)</a></strong>. The CRB will then vote on whether or not to grant Recognition to the prospective club.<br /><br /></li><li>Representatives from the prospective club will be given the opportunity to answer questions posed by the CRB and defend the mission and purpose of the club. You will be notified by email about the CRB&#39;s decision.<br /><br /></li><li>If your club is approved for Recognized, you must meet with the Clubs Graduate Assistant to get Club and Advisor Handbooks and find out what will be required of you as a club each year.<br /><br /></li><li>If your <strong>club</strong> is not approved for Recognition, you will be told why it was denied and the CRB Chair or Clubs Graduate Assistant will be available to tell you what your prospective club needs to do to become a recognized club at RIT.<br /></li></ol>','2010-09-13 11:20:30','mas1042','clubs','howto','Clubs | How to form a Club'),(56,0,'<strong>2006-07 Greek Awards and Recognition</strong><br /><em><br />President&#39;s Cup Award</em><strong><br /></strong>Alpha Sigma Alpha Sorority<br /><br /><br /> <em>President&#39;s Cup Finalist</em><br /> Lamda Pi Chi Sorority, Inc.<br /><br /><em><br />President&#39;s Cup Finalist</em><br />Phi Kappa Psi Fraternity<br /><br /><strong><br /></strong><em>Excellence in Scholastic Achievement</em><br />Delta Phi Epsilon Sorority<br /><br /><em><br />Excellence in Chapter Management</em><br />Triangle Fraternity<br /><br /><strong><br /></strong><em>Excellence in Campus and Community Involvement</em><strong><br /></strong>Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc, Lambda Pi Chi Sorority, Inc.<br /><br /><br /><em>Excellence in Risk Mangagement, Awareness, and Education</em><br />Sigma Alpha Mu Fraternity<br /><br /><br /><em>Excellence in Recruitment and Retention</em><br />Zeta Tau Alpha Fraternity<br /><br /><strong><br /></strong><em>College Panhellenic Council New Member of the Year </em><br />Kayla Himelein-Zeta Tau Alpha Sorority<br /><br /><br /><em>Inter-Fraternity Council New Member of the Year</em><br />Edward Wolf-Alpha Epsilon Pi Fraternity<p><em><br />College Panhellenic Council Scholar of the Year</em><br />Annais Rhoden-Lambda Pi Chi Sorority, Inc.<br /><br /><em><br /></em> <em>Inter-Fraternity Council Scholar of the Year</em><strong><br /></strong>Robert Hoy-Phi Kappa Psi Fraternity<br /><br /><em><br />National Pan-Hellenic Council Scholar of the Year</em><br />Brittnay Ray-Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc.<br /><br /><br /><em>Oustanding Greek Achiever</em><br />Mark Keramaty-Sigma Alpha Mu Fraternity<br /><em><br /><br />President of the Year</em><br />Ashley Hennigan-Alpha Sigma Alpha Sorority<br /><br /><br /><em>Theta Xi Scholarship</em><br />Angelina Faulkner-Alpha Xi Delta Sorority, Mark Keramaty-Sigma Alpha Mu Fraternity<br /><br /><br /><em>GAMMA Educational Program of the Year</em><br />Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc.-HIV/Aids Testing<br /><br /><br /><em>GAMMA Member of the Year</em><strong><em><br /></em></strong>Jamie Winch-Alpha Xi Delta Sorority</p><p><em><br />Inter-Fraternity Delegate of the Year</em><br />Matteo Blanc-Alpha Epsilon Pi Fraternity<br /><br /><br /><em>Inter-Fraternity Council E-Board Member of the Year</em><br />Richard Allen-Tau Kappa Epsilon Fraternity</p><p><em><br />National Pan-Hellenic Council Man of the Year</em><br />Richard Bailey-Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity, Inc.<br /><br /><br /><em>National Pan-Hellenic Council Woman of the Year</em><br />Erica Holder-Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc.<br /><em><br /><br />National Pan-Hellenic Unity Award</em><br />Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, Inc.<br /><em><br /><br />National Pan-Hellenic E-Board Member of the Year</em><strong><br /></strong>Raymour Nosworthy-Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity, Inc.<br /><br /><br /><em>National Pan-Hellenic Council &quot;Who Runs the Yard&quot;</em><br />Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc.<br /><br /><br /><em>College Panhellenic Council Delegate of the Year</em><br />Hallie Schiff-Zeta Tau Alpha Sorority</p><p><br /><em>College Panhellenic Council E-Board Member of the Year</em><br />Joanne Okvath-Alpha Sigma Alpha Sorority</p><p><strong><br /></strong><em>College Panhellenic Spirit Award</em><br />Zeta Tau Alpha Sorority<br /><br /><br /><em>College Panhellenic Council New Member Class</em><br />Alpha Xi Delta Sorority, Spring 2006</p><p><br /><em>College Panhellenic Council Adelphia Award</em><br />Carol Callesano-Delta Phi Epsilon Sorority</p>','2007-08-01 11:55:37','1','fratsorlife','awards','Resources | Awards and Recognition'),(52,0,'<p><strong>GAMMA</strong><br /> 		&quot;Greeks Advocating the Mature Management of Alcohol&quot; <br /> The BACCHUS and GAMMA Peer Education Network is an international association of college and university based peer education programs focusing on alcohol abuse prevention and other related student health and safety issues. </p>  		<p>GAMMA is not a group of students whose purpose is to convince students not to drink; rather, it is an organization that encourages that when people drink they do so in a manner in which they do not cause harm to themselves or others. GAMMA&rsquo;s sponsors projects such as Taxi Cab business cards, Alcohol Awareness Fairs, Safe Spring Break, alcohol and other drug speakers, and educational forums.</p> 	  <p><strong>Greek Newsletter</strong><br /> Between The Columns, a publication from the Office of Greek Life, is a monthly newsletter highlighting outstanding individual and chapter accomplishments as well as what is happening in the Greek system. The newsletter is available online during in school session. Check out our <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/greek/resources/newsletter.php\" title=\"Between the Columns\">latest issue</a>.</p> 		 		<p><strong>Honor Societies</strong><br /> Being one of the top leaders is an honor worthy of prestigious recognition. Rochester Institute of Technology is proud to offer members of the Greek community The National Order of Omega, Rho Lambda, and Gamma Sigma Alpha Honor Societies.</p> 		 		<ul><li> 			<p><strong>The National Order of Omega</strong><br /> The Epsilon Xi chapter is RIT&rsquo;s local chapter of The National Order of Omega. Membership is open to qualified junior and senior undergraduate Greek-affiliated students by application each year. </p> 			</li><li> 			<p><strong>Rho Lambda Honor Society</strong><br /> Rho Lambda is the National Panhellenic Recognition Honor Society. RIT&rsquo;s Gamma Xi chapter was charter August 15, 1994. It is now one of 104 active chapters in the nation. Candidates for membership must submit an application to the Office of Greek Life. Rho Lambda will then extend an invitation to those who qualify. </p> 			</li><li> 			<p><strong>Gamma Sigma Alpha</strong><br /> Juniors or Seniors with a 3.5 cumulative grade point average are eligible for membership. The Eta chapter at RIT was chartered September 10, 1992.</p> 			</li></ul> 						 		<p><strong>Tree of Angels</strong><br /> This annual project is where the Greek community celebrates the holiday season of giving with a lighting of the Greek Angel Tree to benefit East House of Rochester, a non-profit mental health agency. RIT Greek students &ldquo;adopt&rdquo; families and purchase gifts for less fortunate children and grandchildren of East House residents. Each December gifts are placed under the tree during a ceremony and were eventually given to an East House representative for distribution to the families.</p> 		 		<p><strong>Adopt A Highway</strong><br /> Each year the Greek community joins forces to clean up and preserve its surrounding community via the Adopt A Highway program. RIT&rsquo;s Greeks beautify a section of East River Road during Brick City Festival.</p> 		   		<p><strong>Greek Weekend</strong><br /> Greek Weekend is a weekend set aside for fraternity and sorority members to come together to compete in athletic games, serve the Rochester community, and most importantly, have fun while doing it. </p> 		 		<p><strong>NGLA</strong><br /> The Northeast Greek Leadership Association exists to promote the founding principles and positive traditions of all Greek letter organizations through opportunities that encourage learning and leadership for the Northeast region. Hundreds of fraternity and sorority leaders from the Northeast attend the Annual Meeting each year to participate in three days of workshops, general sessions and idea sharing. Each participant&#39;s conference fee includes conference materials and programs; Thursday&#39;s welcome reception, lunch Friday and Saturday; and Saturday evening&#39;s closing banquet. Our awards program allows us to recognize the outstanding efforts of Greek governing councils and celebrate our accomplishments. RIT encourages all Greek members to attend.</p> 		 		<p><strong>Greek Housing</strong><br /> Fraternities and sororities at RIT offer a wide variety of housing options to members. Each offers different benefits for chapter members. The newest additions are the freestanding houses located on the West side of campus next to the Crossroads complex, referred to as the Greek Circle. Currently, there are four fraternities and two sororities living there. The houses offer suite-style double rooms, in-house laundry facilities, a chapter room, and a large social room adjoining a full kitchen.</p> 		 		<p>You will also find six chapters residing on the East - residence halls - end of campus. These houses are specially renovated dorm floors that offer lounges and, in some cases, large basements for chapter recreation and activities. </p> 		 		<p>A full half of the chapters at RIT do not have an &quot;official&quot; house. These groups function with either one or more off-campus apartments, or in a few cases, an off-campus house. Members find this situation beneficial because it allows them live where they want and with friends that are non-members, if desired.</p>','2007-07-20 13:28:30','1','fartsorlife','programs','Resources | Programs'),(53,0,'<strong>Awards and Recognition<br /><br /> </strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;  <a href=\"fratsorlife/awards\" title=\"2006-2007 Awards\">2006-2007 Awards</a><br /><br /><br /><strong>Honor Societies<br /> </strong><br /> Being one of the top leaders is an honor worthy of prestigious recognition. Rochester Institute of Technology is proud to offer members of the Greek community The National Order of Omega, Rho Lambda, and Gamma Sigma Alpha Honor Societies. <ul><li> 			<p><strong>The National Order of Omega</strong><br /> The Epsilon Xi chapter is RIT&rsquo;s local chapter of The National Order of Omega. Membership is open to qualified junior and senior undergraduate Greek-affiliated students by application each year. </p> 			</li><li> 			<p><strong>Rho Lambda Honor Society</strong><br /> Rho Lambda is the National Panhellenic Recognition Honor Society. RIT&rsquo;s Gamma Xi chapter was charter August 15, 1994. It is now one of 104 active chapters in the nation. Candidates for membership must submit an application to the Office of Greek Life. Rho Lambda will then extend an invitation to those who qualify. </p> 			</li><li> 			<p><strong>Gamma Sigma Alpha</strong><br /> Juniors or Seniors with a 3.5 cumulative grade point average are eligible for membership. The Eta chapter at RIT was chartered September 10, 1992.<br />     <br /> </p> 			</li></ul> 						 		<p><strong>Tree of Angels<br /> </strong><br /> This annual project is where the Greek community celebrates the holiday season of giving with a lighting of the Greek Angel Tree to benefit East House of Rochester, a non-profit mental health agency. RIT Greek students &ldquo;adopt&rdquo; families and purchase gifts for less fortunate children and grandchildren of East House residents. Each December gifts are placed under the tree during a ceremony and were eventually given to an East House representative for distribution to the families.<br /> <br /> </p> 		 		<p><strong>Adopt A Highway<br /> </strong><br /> Each year the Greek community joins forces to clean up and preserve its surrounding community via the Adopt A Highway program. RIT&rsquo;s Greeks beautify a section of East River Road during Brick City Festival.<br /> <br /> </p> 		   		<p><strong>Greek Weekend<br /> </strong><br /> Greek Weekend is a weekend set aside for fraternity and sorority members to come together to compete in athletic games, serve the Rochester community, and most importantly, have fun while doing it.<br /> <br />  </p> 		 		<p><strong>NGLA<br /> </strong><br /> The Northeast Greek Leadership Association exists to promote the founding principles and positive traditions of all Greek letter organizations through opportunities that encourage learning and leadership for the Northeast region. Hundreds of fraternity and sorority leaders from the Northeast attend the Annual Meeting each year to participate in three days of workshops, general sessions and idea sharing. Each participant&#39;s conference fee includes conference materials and programs; Thursday&#39;s welcome reception, lunch Friday and Saturday; and Saturday evening&#39;s closing banquet. Our awards program allows us to recognize the outstanding efforts of Greek governing councils and celebrate our accomplishments. RIT encourages all Greek members to attend.<br /> <br /> </p> 		 		<p><strong>Greek Housing<br /> </strong><br /> Fraternities and sororities at RIT offer a wide variety of housing options to members. Each offers different benefits for chapter members. The newest additions are the freestanding houses located on the West side of campus next to the Crossroads complex, referred to as the Greek Circle. Currently, there are four fraternities and two sororities living there. The houses offer suite-style double rooms, in-house laundry facilities, a chapter room, and a large social room adjoining a full kitchen.</p> 		 		<p>You will also find six chapters residing on the East - residence halls - end of campus. These houses are specially renovated dorm floors that offer lounges and, in some cases, large basements for chapter recreation and activities. </p> 		 		<p>A full half of the chapters at RIT do not have an &quot;official&quot; house. These groups function with either one or more off-campus apartments, or in a few cases, an off-campus house. Members find this situation beneficial because it allows them live where they want and with friends that are<br />  non-members, if desired.<br /> <br /> <strong>Greek Newsletter<br /> </strong><br /> Between The Columns, a publication from the Office of Greek Life, is a monthly newsletter highlighting outstanding individual and chapter accomplishments as well as what is happening in the Greek system. The newsletter is available online during in school session.</p>','2007-08-08 14:50:43','1','fratsorlife','programs','Resources | Programs'),(63,0,'<strong>Membership Recruitment Process, what Is It?<br /> </strong>  <br /> Recruitment is a two-way process by which members of a fraternity/sorority chapter decide who they would best like to join their organization. At the same time, you, the potential new member decides which chapter interests you the most. The recruitment process is a great opportunity to meet active members, to hear their activities, values, and ideals. However, participation in recruitment does not obligate you to join.<br /><br />    <p> <strong>How Do I Decide?<br /> </strong><br /> Each person looks for different aspects in a particular fraternity/sorority. While all chapters place emphasis on academics, some chapters are also known for a focus on athletics, community service, or friendship. Most chapters encourage a well-rounded approach. The choice is up to you. Look at all the chapters and evaluate which best meets your needs and interest.<br /><br /> </p>   <p> <strong>How Should I Act During Recruitment?</strong><br />   <br />Rule number one is to be yourself. You want to know what the chapter is like and they want to know the real you. Therefore, be yourself and do not put up a &quot;front.&quot;<br /><br /> </p>   <p> <strong>Before I Join, What Do I Need To Know?</strong><br />   <br />Joining a fraternity/sorority carries certain responsibilities. Make sure you know the entire financial obligation that is required. Costs will vary from chapter to chapter, but expenses will generally include quarterly, local and national dues as well as one time new member and initiation fees. Furthermore, you should understand all the aspects of membership that are required for initiation into the chapter. Do not hesitate to ask questions. Active members will be more than willing to help you out.<br /><br /> </p>   <p><strong>What Happens When I Become A New Member?</strong><br />   <br /> A potential new member becomes a new member when he/she accepts a bid to become a member. As a new member you will partake in an education period during which you are prepared for active membership. The length of the new member period varies. During this time you are involved in a variety of activities, all designed to enable the new members to become a part of the brotherhood/sisterhood. Such activities include becoming acquainted with your chapter&#39;s history, its goals, how it functions, and your key to its future. As each new member brings new life into the chapter, each chapter will bring something new into the life of each of you who join. Once you become an initiated member of a national fraternity and sorority, you are ineligible for membership in any other fraternity/sorority. Being a new member is a time to learn about college, your chapter, and especially yourself. However, requiring new member to engage in any type of prank or hazing activity is prohibited. If you feel you have been subject to such behavior, contact the Office of Fraternity &amp; Sorority Life at 585-475-7123.</p>','2008-09-16 12:37:25','1','fratsorlife','recruitment','Resources | Recruitment'),(61,0,'<strong>Why vend at RIT?</strong><br /><p>Vending at RIT is a great opportunity to sell products and services to potentially thousands of students, faculty and staff members.</p>      	<p>Assistance from a student organization is available during your visit to RIT. You may select or our office can assign you a sponsor group. This group will contact you a few days before your visit and help to meet your vending needs. Your sponsor group is available to help you unload and load your items, set up and clean up and to give you a break during the day. Sponsor groups are students of RIT, and therefore, they are not available to stay with the vendor the whole day due to classes, but they are expected to help the vendor as much as possible.<br /><br /><strong>Vending Locations</strong><br /><br />There are two locations on campus where venders are permits to sell. The lobby of the Student Alumni Union (SAU) is our most popular vending location. The SAU is a central place for many campus offices and activities. This is also the location of two cafeterias, Ben and Jerry&#39;s Ice Cream and the RIT Candy Counter; all popular and busy places for RIT students, faculty and staff. Vending at RIT is a great opportunity to reach a wide range of possible customers. Grace Watson Hall is our other vending location, located on the residential side of campus. Grace Watson houses the largest dining hall on campus and is connected to two our residence halls, home to over 1,300 students, especially during the lunch and dinner times.</p><p><strong>Cost of vending at RIT<br /><br /></strong>Vending in the SAU is available from 9:00 AM to 4:30 PM on Thursdays and Fridays only. The cost to reserve a table in the SAU is $50, however, a second and third table only cost $6 each (a total of $62 for three tables). Vending in Grace Watson Hall is available each weekday from 9:00 AM to 7:00 PM, but no tables are provided. There are a limited number of spaces so please remember to book early. Payment for vending is due the day of the reservation and can be paid in cash or check. If cash is used, the exact amount must be given.<br /><br /><strong>Vendor Contract</strong><br /><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" />&nbsp;  <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/sau/vending/agreement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Vendor Agreement</a><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" />&nbsp; <a href=\"http://campuslife.rit.edu/sau/vending/gracewatson_agreement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Grace Watson Vendor Agreement</a></p><p><br /><strong>Prohibited vending items</strong></p><p>The following items may not be sold by vendors:</p>   	<ul><li>Credit Cards</li><li>Candles or other open flame devices</li><li>Incense and potpourri</li><li>Touchier style lamps, including but not limited to those that use halogen, incandescent or fluorescent bulbs</li><li>Fog machines and similar devices<br /></li></ul><p><strong><br />Student vendors</strong><br /><br />If you are an RIT student who is interested in vending at RIT, you may reserve tables at a reduced cost. Reserving a table/vending space is only $25 for the first table. Any additional tables (up to a total of three tables) are $6 each.<br /> <br /> <br /> <strong>Do you have any questions?</strong><br /> <br /> <img src=\"images/link.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"click link\" title=\"click link\" align=\"left\" />&nbsp;    <a href=\"sau/faq\">Vending FAQ</a> </p>','2007-08-30 13:51:58','1','sau','vending','Services | RIT Vending '),(65,0,'Main topics are explained below in effort to answer some frequently asked questions. If you still have questions not covered in CCL FAQ please call the Center for Campus Life at 585.475.7058.<br /> <br />  <p><strong>I need to meet with a member of the CCL Staff, should I make an Appointment</strong><strong>?</strong><em><br /> </em>Yes, please make an appointment. Please review the Professional Staff page to find out the office hours of each individual. You may also call the Center for Campus Life at 585.475.7058 to set up an appointment with any staff member. </p><p> <br /> <strong>What is an Artist Request Form?</strong><br /> These forms are for requesting the services of Center for Campus Life Staff Artists. You may request banners, poster, fliers, and other projects by special request. These Forms are located only online by visiting http://campuslife.rit.edu/art_request </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"> <strong><br />  Where can I locate the</strong><strong> </strong><strong>Bathrooms</strong><strong> in the SAU?</strong><br /> Bathrooms are located on the main floor of the SAU by the Fireside Lounge, upstairs on the mezzanine level directly to the right of the stairs, and on the A-level near the Ritz Sports Zone. <br /> </p>    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>How can I reserve a </strong><strong>Display Case?</strong><br /> Display cases can be reserved at SAU Reservations (behind the Info Desk). The gallery case by Fireside Lounge has to be reserved through the Student Government Art Committee.<br />  </p>    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong> When is Event Registration (EVR) open?</strong><br />EVR is open every day from 1pm to 4pm. More information about EVR can be found on the <a href=\"/main/admin/editPage/sau/evr\" title=\"Event Registration\"><strong>Plan Your Event</strong></a> page. <br />   </p>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong>What </strong><strong>Events on Campus are happening this week?</strong><br /> Visit http://events.rit.edu for a complete list. <br /> Also, CCL runs the EventsAtRIT screen name on AOL, @EventsAtRIT on Twitter, and the EventsAtRIT Facebook page.</p>      <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong> I lost something, where can I find the Lost &amp; Found?</strong><br /> Located at: SAU Information Desk, Bausch &amp; Lomb Center Information Desk, Ellingson Hall, Department of Public Safety, Grace Watson Hall.<strong> </strong></p>    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><br />What is an</strong><strong> Ombudsman?</strong><br /> Student Ombudsman (pronounced OM&#39;-BUDZ-MEN): One who investigates reported complaints from students, reports findings, and helps to achieve equitable settlements. The Ombuds office is located in the SAU, room 1110 (in the RITreat).</p>  <strong><br />How can I get a </strong><strong>Quarterly Calendar?</strong><br /> The Center for Campus Life Marketing and Publicity Team publishes a quarterly calendar of on campus events. Calendars are mailed to commuter students residing locally, distributed by Resident Advisors and Community Advocates to students in the Residence Halls, Apartments and the RIT Inn. Additional copies are available at the Information Desk in the lobby of the Student Alumni Union. <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong> <br />Who can make </strong><strong>Reservations?</strong><strong><br /></strong> SAU Reservations is located behind the Info Desk. Student groups, staff, and faculty can reserve rooms in the SAU and in academic buildings. Display cases and tables can also be reserved through SAU Reservations. The phone number is 585.475.6992 and email address is reserve@rit.edu.&nbsp;  </p>    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong> How can I get a copy of The Source?</strong><br />Source Books are available in the Off-Campus and Apartment Student Association (OCASA) Office located in the RITreat of the Student Alumni Union. <strong><a href=\"/thesource/\" title=\"The Source Handbook Online\">The Source</a></strong> is also available online. </p>          <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><br /> Student Affairs is located where?</strong><br /> Student Affairs is located on the mezzanine level of the SAU.<br /><br /> <strong><br />Student Conduct Office is located where?</strong><br /> The Student Conduct Office is located on the mezzanine level of the SAU in room 2460.<br /> <br />  </p>    <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Where can I purchase</strong><strong> Tickets?</strong><br />Tickets for major events are sold at the Gordon Field House Box Office (475-4121).  </p>  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong> Where is Vending located?</strong><br /> RIT Vending is located behind the Info Desk. The phone number is 585.475.5248.<br /> Hours change quarterly. More info can be found on the <a href=\"/main/admin/editPage/sau/vending\" title=\"RIT Vending\"><strong>RIT Vending</strong></a> page.</p>','2010-09-13 11:23:17','cclwww','about','FAQ','Center for Campus Life FAQ'),(66,0,'<strong>Large Concert</strong><br /><br />Possible Events:<br />    <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; CAB Concerts- Lupe Fiasco<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Club Concerts- Mi Tierra<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Comedians- Lisa Lampanelli<br /><br /><br />Typical Equipment:<br />        <br />    <em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sound System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4 hi speakers/side<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4 subwoofers/side<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 12 stage monitor speakers<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 stage monitor control console<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 house control console<br />        <br />   <em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lighting System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 60 lights down stage on truss<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 48 lights up stage on truss<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 lighting contr